<section xml:id="section-arithmetic">

    <title>Arithmetic with Whole Numbers, Decimals, and Natural Exponents</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>From daily life, most of us are familiar with how the basic mathematical operations <mdash /> addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division <mdash /> work. In this section, we'll discuss each operation briefly, and develop a few techniques to help us make sense of these operations as we study algebra.</p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Addition</title>
        <index><main>addition</main></index>

        <p>When we consider counting, <term>addition</term> simply means <q>more.</q> Starting with three apples, then getting two more gives:<me>\text{&#127823; &#127823; &#127823;} + \text{&#127823; &#127823;} = \text{&#127823; &#127823; &#127823; &#127823; &#127823;}</me></p>

        <p>It doesn't matter if we add two apples to three apples or three apples to two apples, either way we end up with five apples. Order isn't important for addition.<me>3+2=2+3</me>They both equal <m>5</m>. When the order of an operation doesn't matter, mathematicians say the operation is <term>commutative</term>.</p>

        <p>For small <term>whole numbers</term> (<m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, <m>4</m>, etc.) we can add by counting. For larger whole numbers, we use an algorithm if we need to add by hand. Over the centuries, people have developed many algorithms that work. Adding <m>697</m> apples to <m>223</m> apples, here are two possible algorithms:</p>

        <!--animated versions of algorithms? perhaps as "solutions"?-->
        <algorithm>
            <statement>
                <sidebyside>
                    <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrrr}
                        \amp\phantom{_1} \amp\phantom{_1} \amp   \\
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp \phantom{9 }\amp \phantom{2 }\amp \phantom{0}
                        \end{array}
                    </me></p>
                    <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrrr}
                        \amp\phantom{_1} \amp\highlight{_1} \amp   \\
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp \phantom{9 }\amp \phantom{2 }\amp \highlight{0}
                        \end{array}
                    </me></p>
                    <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrrr}
                        \amp\highlight{_1} \amp_1 \amp   \\
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp \phantom{9 }\amp \highlight{2} \amp 0
                        \end{array}
                    </me></p>
                    <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrrr}
                        \amp_1 \amp_1 \amp   \\
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp \highlight{9} \amp 2 \amp 0
                        \end{array}
                    </me></p>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
        </algorithm>

        <algorithm>
            <statement>
                <sidebyside>
                   <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrr}
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp \phantom{8} \amp \phantom{0} \amp \phantom{0} \\
                        \amp \phantom{1} \amp \phantom{1} \amp \phantom{0} \\
                        \amp \phantom{1} \amp \phantom{0} \\
                        %\hline{}
                        \amp \phantom{9} \amp \phantom{2} \amp \phantom{0}
                        \end{array}
                   </me></p>
                   <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrr}
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp \highlight{8} \amp \highlight{0} \amp \highlight{0} \\
                        \amp \phantom{1} \amp \phantom{1} \amp \phantom{0} \\
                        \amp \phantom{1} \amp \phantom{0} \\
                        %\hline{}
                        \amp \phantom{9} \amp \phantom{2} \amp \phantom{0}
                        \end{array}
                   </me></p>
                   <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrr}
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp 8 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                        \amp \highlight{1} \amp \highlight{1} \amp \highlight{0} \\
                        \amp \amp \phantom{1} \amp \phantom{0} \\
                        %\hline{}
                        \amp \phantom{9} \amp \phantom{2} \amp \phantom{0}
                        \end{array}
                   </me></p>
                   <p><me>
                        \begin{array}{rrr}
                        \amp 6 \amp 9 \amp 7 \\
                        + \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp 8 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                        \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                        \amp \amp \highlight{1} \amp \highlight{0} \\
                        \hline{}
                        \amp \highlight{9} \amp \highlight{2} \amp \highlight{0}
                        \end{array}
                
                   </me></p>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
        </algorithm>

        <p>Do you see how both algorithms work? (The first one should be familiar, the second might require some thought.) Whether we add by hand or use technology (calculator, computer, cell phone, etc.) we have <m>697 + 223 = 920</m>.</p>

        <p>In mathematics, we call each number being added together a <term>term</term>, and the result of addition is called a <term>sum</term>.<index><main>term</main></index><index><main>sum</main></index> In your algebra course, you may be required to perform calculations by hand on exams. Here are a few practice problems.</p>

