    <subsection>
        <title>Multiplication</title>
        <index><main>multiplication</main></index>

        <p>There's more than one way to think about <term>multiplication</term>. For counting, multiplication helps us compute the number of cats in the table below.</p>

        <table>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                    <cell>&#128049;</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>If we notice three rows with four cats each, we have<me>\overbrace{4 + 4 + 4}^{3\text{ times}} = 3 \times 4 = 12 \text{ cats},</me> but if we notice four columns with three cats each, that's <me>\overbrace{3 + 3 + 3 + 3}^{4 \text{times}} = 4 \times 3 = 12 \text{ cats}.</me> Either way, multiplication can serve as shorthand for repeated addition. And it's clear that the order of the <term>factors</term><index><main>factor</main></index> (the numbers we multiply together) has no effect on the value of the <term>product</term><index><main>product</main></index> (the result of multiplication). Multiplication, like addition, is a commutative operation.</p>

        <p>Multiplication isn't always a shortcut for repeated addition. We also use multiplication for <em>scaling</em>. If a map's scale is <q><m>1</m> inch to <m>2</m> miles</q>, a distance of <m>4</m> inches on the map would translate into <m>4\cdot2=8</m> miles for the actual distance.</p>

