    <subsection>
        <title>Division</title>
        <index><main>division</main></index>

        <p>Whenever we share evenly, we are using <term>division</term>. Imagine there are <m>18</m> candies. If <m>2</m> people want to share them evenly, each person gets <m>18 \div 2 = 9</m> candies. (The symbol <m>\div</m> is one symbol used for division.) The order of division matters <mdash /> there's no way to divide the <m>2</m> people by <m>18</m>. The order of division matters <mdash /> division is <em>not</em> commutative.</p>

        <p>The result of division is called <term>quotient</term>.<index><main>quotient</main></index> As we wrote above, one way to denote division is with the <m>\div</m> symbol, as in <m>18\div2</m>. A fraction bar also denotes division, as in <m>\frac{18}{2}</m>.</p>

        <p>Multiplication and division are inverse operations. For example:<md>
                <mrow>\amp3\cdot4=12\amp\frac{12}{3}=4</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp2\cdot5=10\amp\frac{10}{2}=5</mrow>
            </md>This implies we can use multiplication to do division. For example, when we calculate <m>\frac{54}{9}</m>, we think: <m>9</m> times what equals <m>54</m>? Since <m>9\cdot6=54</m>, we have <m>\frac{54}{9}=6</m>.</p>
<!--
        <p>The quotient from a division might be a whole number or it might not be. When dividing with small numbers, simply knowing your multiplication table is quite helpful. For instance, can you calculate <m>\frac{54}{9}</m>? If you know the multiplication table well enough to recognize that <m>54</m> comes from <m>9\times6</m>, then dividing this number by <m>9</m> evidently makes <m>6</m>.</p>
-->
        <p>When the result is not going to be a whole number, or larger numbers are being divided, then division is the most time-consuming of the four basic arithmetic operations. There are algorithms like the long division algorithm (detailed at <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_division#Method">Wikipedia</url> and elsewhere) to compute a quotient by hand. Or perhaps you have access to an electronic calculator.</p>

        <warning>
            <title>Division by Zero</title>
            <p>What if we try to divide a number by <m>0</m> (that is, if we use <m>0</m> as a divisor)? Let's see:<md>
                    <mrow>\frac{12}{3}\amp=4\amp\quad\text{as }\amp3\cdot4=12</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{10}{2}\amp=5\amp\quad\text{as }\amp2\cdot5=10</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{0}{2}\amp=0\amp\quad\text{as }\amp2\cdot0=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{2}{0}\amp=?\amp\quad\text{as }\amp0\cdot?=2</mrow>
                </md>Since we cannot find such a number that satisfies <m>0\cdot?=2</m>, we cannot divide any number by <m>0</m>. Mathematicians say that such an effort gives an <term>undefined</term> result. For example, <m>\frac{2}{0}</m> is undefined. However, we can see it's ok to do <m>\frac{0}{2}=0</m>, because <m>2\cdot0=0</m>.</p>
        </warning>

        <p>Here are some division exercises that most instructors would expect you to be able to do <em>without</em> the aid of a calculator.</p>

        <exercise>
            <introduction>
                <p>Perform each division by hand, then check your results.</p>
            </introduction>
            <webwork>
                <statement>
                    <p><ol label="a">
                        <li>
                            <p>Divide <m>99</m> by <m>3</m>.</p>
                            <p><var name="33" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Divide <m>35\div5</m>.</p>
                            <p><var name="7" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Divide <m>\dfrac{4200}{60}</m>.</p>
                            <p><var name="70" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Divide <m>11.8</m> by <m>2</m>.</p>
                            <p><var name="5.9" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Exponentiation (Raising to Powers)</title>
        <index><main>exponentiation</main></index>

        <p>On occasion, we may need to multiply by the same number over and over again. For example, suppose we place a bet of <m>\$5.00</m> with the <q>double or nothing</q> rules. (So if we win, our money is doubled, but if we lose, it's all gone.) What if we won four times in a row, and after each win placed a bet with all that we had won? We'd end up with this much money:<me>\$5.00\overbrace{{}\cdot2\cdot2\cdot2\cdot2}^{4\text{ times}}</me>Rather than write so many <q><m>{}\cdot2</m>,</q> there is this notation:<me>\$5.00\cdot2^4</me></p>

        <p>To calculate <m>5\cdot2^4</m>, we do:<md>
                <mrow>5\cdot2^4\amp=5\cdot(2\cdot2\cdot2\cdot2)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=5\cdot16</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=80</mrow>
            </md></p>

<!--        
        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <pg-macros>
                    <macro-file>contextCurrency.pl</macro-file>
                </pg-macros>
                <setup>
                    <var name="$alot">
                        <static>\$80</static>
                    </var>
                    <pg-code>
                        Context("Currency");
                        $alot=Currency("80");
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>How much money do we have if we walk away with <m>\$5.00\cdot2^4</m>?</p>
                    <p><var name="$alot" width="10" /></p>
                </statement>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
-->

        <p>So an expression like <m>2^4</m> means to multiply repeatedly. The number being multiplied (in this case, <m>2</m>) is called the <term>base</term> and the number of times it is multiplied (in this case, <m>4</m>) is called the <term>exponent</term>. All together, <m>2^4</m> is a <term>power</term> (specifically, a power of <m>2</m>).</p>

        <p>Check your understanding with a few exercises.</p>

        <exercise>
            <introduction>
                <p>Calculate each of the following by hand, then check your results.</p>
            </introduction>
            <webwork>
                <statement>
                    <p><ol label="a">
                        <li>
                            <p>Calculate <m>2^3</m>.</p>
                            <p><var name="8" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Find <m>3</m> raised to the fourth power.</p>
                            <p><var name="81" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Compute <m>1^{42}</m>.</p>
                            <p><var name="1" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Calculate <m>9\cdot5^2</m>.</p>
                            <p><var name="225" width="10" /></p>
                        </li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>Vocabulary Summary</title>

        <p>There is a lot of vocabulary that goes along with basic arithmetic, and even many people who can <em>do</em> the arithmetic are unsure of the right words to discuss the process. Here we summarize the vocabulary from this section.</p>

        <table>
            <caption>Math operations vocabulary</caption>
            <tabular valign="top" top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor">
                <col width="30%" />
                <col />
                <col />
                <col />
                <col right="major"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell>symbol</cell>
                    <cell>operation</cell>
                    <cell>first number</cell>
                    <cell>second number</cell>
                    <cell>result</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                    <cell>add</cell>
                    <cell colspan="2" halign="center">each is a term</cell>
                    <cell>sum</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-</m></cell>
                    <cell>subtract</cell>
                    <cell colspan="2" halign="center">each is a term</cell>
                    <cell>difference</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><p><m>\cdot</m>, <m>\times</m>, or no symbol at all</p></cell>
                    <cell>multiply</cell>
                    <cell colspan="2" halign="center">each is a factor</cell>
                    <cell>product</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><p><m>\div</m>, or written with a fraction bar</p></cell>
                    <cell>divide</cell>
                    <cell>dividend</cell>
                    <cell>divisor</cell>
                    <cell>quotient</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="major">
                    <cell><p><m>\hat{ }</m>, or second number written in superscript</p></cell>
                    <cell>exponentiate</cell>
                    <cell>base</cell>
                    <cell>exponent</cell>
                    <cell>power</cell>
                </row>                
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </subsection>

